00:01:37.280 --> 00:01:40.720
So lifecycle management.

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:44.260
So this is my definition of
what lifecycle management is.

00:01:44.260 --> 00:01:48.790
It's essentially the active
engagement of-- it's the active

00:01:48.790 --> 00:01:52.000
engagement of all the
stakeholders with the system,

00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:54.490
between the time when
it starts to operate--

00:01:54.490 --> 00:01:56.020
so you've done
the commissioning,

00:01:56.020 --> 00:01:57.910
you've done the operations--

00:01:57.910 --> 00:02:01.040
until you decide to decommission
and retire the system.

00:02:01.040 --> 00:02:03.700
So it's during the
whole operation life.

00:02:03.700 --> 00:02:05.200
And what you want
to do, is you want

00:02:05.200 --> 00:02:07.320
to maximize the
value that you gain

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:09.139
from the system's existence.

00:02:09.139 --> 00:02:11.740
And so life cycle
management starts

00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:14.170
from the very, very, very start.

00:02:14.170 --> 00:02:16.140
And so I listed
here some activities

00:02:16.140 --> 00:02:18.980
that are included in
lifecycle management.

00:02:18.980 --> 00:02:21.770
So obviously daily operations,
you know monitoring,

00:02:21.770 --> 00:02:25.510
is the system
working as expected?

00:02:25.510 --> 00:02:28.750
Training and certification
of the operators.

00:02:28.750 --> 00:02:30.860
Sometimes, you know,
in long live systems,

00:02:30.860 --> 00:02:34.960
the people who were the early
operators, generation one,

00:02:34.960 --> 00:02:37.300
are not necessarily the
people who are going

00:02:37.300 --> 00:02:38.770
to operate for the whole life.

00:02:38.770 --> 00:02:42.130
So you have to have
new people operate.

00:02:42.130 --> 00:02:44.260
Maybe one of the most
extreme examples of that

00:02:44.260 --> 00:02:46.532
is an airplane
known as the b-52.

00:02:46.532 --> 00:02:47.490
Have you heard of this?

00:02:47.490 --> 00:02:50.530
This airplane might be the
first plane that actually has

00:02:50.530 --> 00:02:52.990
a 100 year operational life.

00:02:52.990 --> 00:02:55.240
And there are apparently Navy--

00:02:55.240 --> 00:02:58.330
Air Force guys at MIT,
you can confirm this,

00:02:58.330 --> 00:03:00.040
that there's actually like--

00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:03.580
the grandfather was
the first generation

00:03:03.580 --> 00:03:06.190
and there's like third
generation pilots now flying

00:03:06.190 --> 00:03:07.690
on the b-52.

00:03:07.690 --> 00:03:09.270
That's what I've been told.

00:03:09.270 --> 00:03:12.554
Did you hear this as well?

00:03:12.554 --> 00:03:15.670
AUDIENCE: Yeah, That's correct.

00:03:15.670 --> 00:03:18.150
PROFESSOR: Do some
of these people?

00:03:18.150 --> 00:03:20.080
AUDIENCE: No, I've
never actually worked

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:23.440
on that airframe.

00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:24.250
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:03:24.250 --> 00:03:25.960
But anyway, so
that's what I mean

00:03:25.960 --> 00:03:29.590
by [INAUDIBLE] not just
the initial operators,

00:03:29.590 --> 00:03:32.200
but over multiple generations.

00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:36.040
Then the third thing
here is servicing.

00:03:36.040 --> 00:03:38.500
And servicing comes
in two flavors,

00:03:38.500 --> 00:03:40.210
of preventive
maintenance, you know

00:03:40.210 --> 00:03:43.390
regular maintenance, and
then corrective maintenance,

00:03:43.390 --> 00:03:45.820
which we also call repair.

00:03:45.820 --> 00:03:49.920
Dealing with small and large
failures, recalls, anomalies.

00:03:49.920 --> 00:03:52.030
This is a big deal in
the automotive industry,

00:03:52.030 --> 00:03:53.440
as we know.

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:55.540
Increasingly
protecting the system

00:03:55.540 --> 00:03:58.480
from either random
or targeted attacks.

00:03:58.480 --> 00:04:03.380
Cyber, physical, right,
physical security but also cyber

00:04:03.380 --> 00:04:06.430
security is becoming
a huge topic.

00:04:06.430 --> 00:04:08.470
Sharing and archiving
the data that's

00:04:08.470 --> 00:04:09.820
being produced by the system.

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:12.762
More and more systems produce
larger amounts of data.

00:04:12.762 --> 00:04:13.970
Well, what do you do with it?

00:04:13.970 --> 00:04:15.850
How do you store that data?

00:04:15.850 --> 00:04:18.670
Upgrading and retrofitting
the system as needed.

00:04:18.670 --> 00:04:21.670
So retrofitting means
we're physically

00:04:21.670 --> 00:04:23.710
changing the configuration
of the system--

00:04:23.710 --> 00:04:27.370
right?-- over its life
to add new capabilities.

00:04:27.370 --> 00:04:31.480
And upgrading; upgrading
can be done sometimes

00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:33.640
without having to
change the hardware.

00:04:33.640 --> 00:04:36.910
So you're doing a software
upgrade, or software update,

00:04:36.910 --> 00:04:38.380
software patching.

00:04:38.380 --> 00:04:40.255
All of this would
go under upgrades.

00:04:42.850 --> 00:04:45.770
Cross strapping the
system with other system

00:04:45.770 --> 00:04:47.680
in a federation of systems.

00:04:47.680 --> 00:04:49.960
So what I mean by
this is a system

00:04:49.960 --> 00:04:53.410
may have been designed
just to operate on its own,

00:04:53.410 --> 00:04:55.540
but now you're connecting
it with another system.

00:04:55.540 --> 00:04:58.351
This happened, for example,
the electrical grid.

00:04:58.351 --> 00:04:58.850
Right?

00:04:58.850 --> 00:05:03.160
The early electrical grids were
local, regional power grids.

00:05:03.160 --> 00:05:05.610
And now we've connected
them, in the US

00:05:05.610 --> 00:05:09.340
we have three major grids, the
eastern, the western, and then

00:05:09.340 --> 00:05:10.900
Texas has its own grid.

00:05:10.900 --> 00:05:13.030
Texas does a lot
of its own stuff.

00:05:13.030 --> 00:05:14.220
It's called ERCCOT.

00:05:14.220 --> 00:05:16.090
And then here in
Europe, you know

00:05:16.090 --> 00:05:19.960
the European electrical grid
is now continental-wide.

00:05:19.960 --> 00:05:21.010
It didn't used to be.

00:05:21.010 --> 00:05:25.720
And of course, that has big
implications for operations.

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:27.355
Reducing the
resource consumption

00:05:27.355 --> 00:05:31.060
and environmental burden
of the system over time,

00:05:31.060 --> 00:05:32.800
and then finally,
decommissioning

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:35.420
the system when
it's time to do so.

00:05:35.420 --> 00:05:38.670
And in many systems,
this is a big challenge

00:05:38.670 --> 00:05:41.020
as to finding when
is the right time

00:05:41.020 --> 00:05:43.060
to decommission the system.

00:05:43.060 --> 00:05:45.100
And that's often the
case when, you know,

00:05:45.100 --> 00:05:48.910
the operating costs exceed the
value that the system delivers.

00:05:48.910 --> 00:05:50.920
So this is a pretty
long list here.

00:05:50.920 --> 00:05:57.410
And a lot of tasks, a lot
of decisions to be made.

00:05:57.410 --> 00:06:00.010
Any questions about this list?

00:06:00.010 --> 00:06:04.180
I don't think it's
complete, but this

00:06:04.180 --> 00:06:07.510
is a lot of things you need to
take care of during operations.

00:06:07.510 --> 00:06:10.200
Here's a more
graphical view of this.

00:06:10.200 --> 00:06:13.930
So this is my sketch of the
systems engineering lifecycle.

00:06:13.930 --> 00:06:16.150
So this is part one, right?

00:06:16.150 --> 00:06:20.290
Conceptual design-- conception,
design, and implementation.

00:06:20.290 --> 00:06:23.440
You start the lifecycle, you
do something like a system

00:06:23.440 --> 00:06:26.740
requirements review, understand
the mission, the requirements,

00:06:26.740 --> 00:06:28.090
the constraints.

00:06:28.090 --> 00:06:31.510
You do conceptual design,
that's where you do creativity,

00:06:31.510 --> 00:06:33.430
architecting, trade studies.

00:06:33.430 --> 00:06:35.127
As a PDR, you choose--

00:06:35.127 --> 00:06:36.710
so in this case, you
know, we're going

00:06:36.710 --> 00:06:38.760
to go through this
triangle concept

00:06:38.760 --> 00:06:41.970
and then you design all
the details within it.

00:06:41.970 --> 00:06:48.570
That's where we do modeling,
simulation, experiments, MDO.

00:06:48.570 --> 00:06:51.000
And we iterate--
sometimes you have

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:54.000
to iterate this
[? dashed ?] duration means

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.210
abandoning the concept you chose
and go for a different concept.

00:06:57.210 --> 00:06:59.940
That's usually undesirable.

00:06:59.940 --> 00:07:02.820
After the CDR, we
implement the system,

00:07:02.820 --> 00:07:05.670
we turn information to
matter, and this all

00:07:05.670 --> 00:07:09.310
happens in a technological,
economic, social context.

00:07:09.310 --> 00:07:14.220
So then, the second part of
it, which in many systems--

00:07:14.220 --> 00:07:18.560
if this is 10 years, this
could be 30 years or more--

00:07:18.560 --> 00:07:20.940
is the actual operational space.

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:24.300
So the system has now been
tested, validated, verified,

00:07:24.300 --> 00:07:25.530
and deployed.

00:07:25.530 --> 00:07:28.830
And now, you know, we
operate the system.

00:07:28.830 --> 00:07:33.340
Things break, we need to service
it, and then I have this--

00:07:33.340 --> 00:07:35.230
you see, there's two
versions of the system.

00:07:35.230 --> 00:07:38.220
One is solid, and the
other one is kind of faint.

00:07:38.220 --> 00:07:40.270
That's the virtual
version of the system.

00:07:40.270 --> 00:07:43.740
So one of the big concepts
that's being pushed now,

00:07:43.740 --> 00:07:47.700
certainly in the US by the
DOD, but also other places.

00:07:47.700 --> 00:07:50.280
Is the idea of a digital twin.

00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:52.500
The idea of a digital
twin is that there's

00:07:52.500 --> 00:07:53.850
a physical system--

00:07:53.850 --> 00:07:55.650
right?-- that exists,
and then there's

00:07:55.650 --> 00:07:58.530
a digital version, a
digital twin of that system,

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:01.890
somewhere on a computer
that mirrors exactly

00:08:01.890 --> 00:08:03.820
what the real system is doing.

00:08:03.820 --> 00:08:06.300
So if something breaks
on the physical system,

00:08:06.300 --> 00:08:09.810
well that same component
fails in the digital twin.

00:08:09.810 --> 00:08:13.230
And then, before you actually
do a repair or any actions,

00:08:13.230 --> 00:08:15.970
you execute those actions
on the digital twin

00:08:15.970 --> 00:08:17.970
to see whether the system
will operate properly.

00:08:20.686 --> 00:08:24.840
And so this is kind of
the latest thinking,

00:08:24.840 --> 00:08:29.130
is that for any system we
should have a digital twin doing

00:08:29.130 --> 00:08:30.390
operations.

00:08:30.390 --> 00:08:31.630
Upgrading the system.

00:08:31.630 --> 00:08:34.440
So in this case, we're
adding things to it,

00:08:34.440 --> 00:08:35.820
we're connecting it.

00:08:35.820 --> 00:08:38.940
You know, and then at some
point, the system does degrade.

00:08:38.940 --> 00:08:41.520
Because, for example,
you know, materials, age,

00:08:41.520 --> 00:08:43.289
they get brittle.

00:08:43.289 --> 00:08:46.050
Technology becomes obsolete.

00:08:46.050 --> 00:08:49.710
You know, it gets harder and
harder to maintain spare parts

00:08:49.710 --> 00:08:52.740
or the suppliers of the
original spare parts

00:08:52.740 --> 00:08:54.060
went out of business.

00:08:54.060 --> 00:08:56.220
So these really
old legacy systems

00:08:56.220 --> 00:08:58.350
can be very
expensive to operate.

00:08:58.350 --> 00:09:00.490
And then at some
point you liquidate

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:03.810
and it's the end
of the life cycle.

00:09:03.810 --> 00:09:06.790
So I've already told you
about one example of this,

00:09:06.790 --> 00:09:08.910
which is the space shuttle.

00:09:08.910 --> 00:09:11.920
And so I'm not going
to belabor this again,

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:14.530
but I think it's a great
opportunity to learn.

00:09:14.530 --> 00:09:19.650
The space shuttle had a 10 year
design life, roughly from 1971

00:09:19.650 --> 00:09:21.750
until '81, first flight.

00:09:21.750 --> 00:09:25.020
And then we operated
the shuttle for 30 years

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:28.710
and we had a total of 135
launches during that time.

00:09:28.710 --> 00:09:33.390
We spent $192 billion dollars
on the shuttle program.

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:36.600
And if you average
that, it's $1.5 billion

00:09:36.600 --> 00:09:40.890
per flight, which is a
lot more than was planned.

00:09:40.890 --> 00:09:43.530
But just yesterday
here at the EPFL,

00:09:43.530 --> 00:09:47.910
we had the annual meeting
of the Swiss Space Center.

00:09:47.910 --> 00:09:52.380
And one of the astronauts
here, Claude Niccolier

00:09:52.380 --> 00:09:55.290
and his colleague,
Professor [? Mehron ?]

00:09:55.290 --> 00:09:57.630
gave a great talk
about the Hubble

00:09:57.630 --> 00:10:00.900
and the servicing of the Hubble
and the amazing things we've

00:10:00.900 --> 00:10:02.160
learned through it.

00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:05.490
And you guys at
MIT, Jeff Hoffman,

00:10:05.490 --> 00:10:09.040
was part of at least the first
servicing mission as well.

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:14.290
So there's incredible things
that were done by the shuttle.

00:10:14.290 --> 00:10:16.860
And so I think we need to
acknowledge that, not just

00:10:16.860 --> 00:10:21.330
the fact that it
was very expensive.

00:10:21.330 --> 00:10:24.300
It accomplished great
things during its life.

00:10:24.300 --> 00:10:27.300
But you know, if we had a chance
to do it again, would we--

00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:29.490
would we come up with
the exact same system,

00:10:29.490 --> 00:10:31.890
would we make all the
same design decisions?

00:10:31.890 --> 00:10:33.240
You know, we lost two of them.

00:10:33.240 --> 00:10:35.820
Probably not, we could probably
do something-- something

00:10:35.820 --> 00:10:36.810
different.

00:10:36.810 --> 00:10:38.940
So here's what we wanted,
and then finally, we

00:10:38.940 --> 00:10:41.770
got a much more complex
system in the end.

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:45.720
And particularly my sense is
that a lot of the things that

00:10:45.720 --> 00:10:49.410
made the shuttle expensive
to operate during its life

00:10:49.410 --> 00:10:51.731
were things related
to maintainability.

00:10:51.731 --> 00:10:52.230
Right?

00:10:52.230 --> 00:10:54.220
Reliability and so forth.

00:10:54.220 --> 00:10:56.160
So the lifecycle
properties, which I

00:10:56.160 --> 00:10:57.310
want to talk about next.

00:10:57.310 --> 00:10:59.470
So I'm just going to
repeat the questions,

00:10:59.470 --> 00:11:01.240
so you guys can hear as well.

00:11:01.240 --> 00:11:03.870
So the question was
about reusability.

00:11:03.870 --> 00:11:05.580
So the shuttle was--

00:11:05.580 --> 00:11:08.460
the orbiter was fully reusable.

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:11.020
The external fuel
tank was not reusable.

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:11.520
Right?

00:11:11.520 --> 00:11:13.200
And then the solid
rocket boosters

00:11:13.200 --> 00:11:15.180
were partially
reusable because they

00:11:15.180 --> 00:11:17.000
had to be stripped
down, you know,

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:20.520
and rebuilt, essentially,
for every launch.

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:24.750
The idea of Blue Origin
and then Space-X Stage One,

00:11:24.750 --> 00:11:27.390
flying it back to
the launch site,

00:11:27.390 --> 00:11:31.320
is absolutely the fact that
if you can make it reusable,

00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:35.490
then you can amortize
the capex in that element

00:11:35.490 --> 00:11:36.820
over multiple flights.

00:11:36.820 --> 00:11:38.500
And it should drop,
you know, the cost

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:41.780
by a factor of
five or 10 or more.

00:11:41.780 --> 00:11:44.380
Now, the devil's in
the details, right?

00:11:44.380 --> 00:11:48.130
So if you start and restart
an engine multiple times,

00:11:48.130 --> 00:11:50.960
you can have a big
transient every time.

00:11:50.960 --> 00:11:53.350
So was this system,
in fact, designed

00:11:53.350 --> 00:11:55.360
to withstand these transients?

00:11:55.360 --> 00:11:58.420
Can it handle multiple starts?

00:11:58.420 --> 00:12:00.040
What does it do
to the materials?

00:12:00.040 --> 00:12:01.530
And so forth.

00:12:01.530 --> 00:12:05.200
And so to really model
this ahead of time,

00:12:05.200 --> 00:12:08.290
and then test it over
the cycles is the key.

00:12:08.290 --> 00:12:11.800
So in the shuttle, the
big problems-- the two

00:12:11.800 --> 00:12:14.260
major subsystems in the
shuttle, in the orbiter,

00:12:14.260 --> 00:12:18.760
in particular that
made it expensive

00:12:18.760 --> 00:12:20.740
and the difference
between the top picture

00:12:20.740 --> 00:12:24.130
and the bottom picture was a,
the TPS, the thermal protection

00:12:24.130 --> 00:12:25.120
system.

00:12:25.120 --> 00:12:29.290
You know, every tile has
hit a different curvature

00:12:29.290 --> 00:12:33.310
in geometry, so really
inspecting every tile,

00:12:33.310 --> 00:12:36.460
replacing tiles, making
sure that the TPS--

00:12:36.460 --> 00:12:39.100
because just one
weakness in the TPS

00:12:39.100 --> 00:12:41.710
could basically be
fatal on re-entry.

00:12:41.710 --> 00:12:45.422
And so, TPS was
very difficult and--

00:12:45.422 --> 00:12:47.380
you know, as opposed to
an ablative heat shield

00:12:47.380 --> 00:12:50.334
that you just sacrifice
the heat shield completely.

00:12:50.334 --> 00:12:52.000
And then the other
was the main engine--

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:53.560
the shuttle main engine.

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:56.890
Originally, the idea was to
only do very deep inspections

00:12:56.890 --> 00:12:59.440
and disassemble-- the
disassembly of the shuttle

00:12:59.440 --> 00:13:02.170
main engine after the
first few test flights,

00:13:02.170 --> 00:13:05.040
and then fly multiple times
without having to really

00:13:05.040 --> 00:13:07.990
re-inspect or
disassemble the engine.

00:13:07.990 --> 00:13:10.422
So they did the
disassembly of the engines

00:13:10.422 --> 00:13:12.130
after the test flights
and then they just

00:13:12.130 --> 00:13:16.210
kept doing it for every flight,
where the original intent was

00:13:16.210 --> 00:13:18.190
to only do it for
the test flights.

00:13:18.190 --> 00:13:22.210
And so the shuttle main engines
were the second big cost driver

00:13:22.210 --> 00:13:23.570
in operations.

00:13:23.570 --> 00:13:28.180
So re-usability is a great
idea, but to the degree

00:13:28.180 --> 00:13:30.220
to which re-usability
actually happens

00:13:30.220 --> 00:13:34.660
in reality, that's really
about detailed design decisions

00:13:34.660 --> 00:13:36.490
you make.

00:13:36.490 --> 00:13:37.430
OK.

00:13:37.430 --> 00:13:39.860
So let me move on then.

00:13:43.440 --> 00:13:48.470
When it comes to really
understanding lifecycle,

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:54.900
I do want to point you to
the 15288 standard, which

00:13:54.900 --> 00:14:01.380
is the ISO 15288 standard,
which has a fairly complete list

00:14:01.380 --> 00:14:03.520
of system lifecycle processes.

00:14:03.520 --> 00:14:06.660
So this is, essentially
the system and software

00:14:06.660 --> 00:14:09.630
engineering, system
lifecycle process standard,

00:14:09.630 --> 00:14:13.770
that has a whole range of
processes that are described

00:14:13.770 --> 00:14:14.970
in quite some detail.

00:14:14.970 --> 00:14:17.670
And they're not just the
technical processes shown here

00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:21.270
on the right side, we focused
a lot on those technical

00:14:21.270 --> 00:14:24.717
processes in this class, the
stakeholders, the requirements,

00:14:24.717 --> 00:14:27.300
the architectural design-- which
is essentially the conceptual

00:14:27.300 --> 00:14:27.960
design--

00:14:27.960 --> 00:14:30.420
but there's also the
project processes, right?

00:14:30.420 --> 00:14:33.540
Executing the project
agreement processes.

00:14:33.540 --> 00:14:36.490
So this would be
negotiating contracts,

00:14:36.490 --> 00:14:39.780
you know supply contracts,
acquisition contracts, and then

00:14:39.780 --> 00:14:41.340
all the organizational
things you

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:44.340
need to do to create the
right organization to execute

00:14:44.340 --> 00:14:45.730
these projects.

00:14:45.730 --> 00:14:49.350
So what's nice about
the 15288 standard

00:14:49.350 --> 00:14:52.691
is that it's a pretty
broad standard.

00:14:52.691 --> 00:14:53.190
OK.

00:14:53.190 --> 00:14:56.520
So let me talk about the ilities
of the lifecycle properties

00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:57.970
in particular.

00:14:57.970 --> 00:15:02.160
What they are and how we
can describe them and how,

00:15:02.160 --> 00:15:04.960
especially how they
relate to each other.

00:15:04.960 --> 00:15:08.250
And so the paper
that underlie this

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:11.310
lecture that you need
to get some more detail.

00:15:11.310 --> 00:15:12.390
And this is one of them.

00:15:12.390 --> 00:15:15.600
So this paper is called
Investigating the Relationships

00:15:15.600 --> 00:15:18.840
and Semantic Sets Among
Lifecycle Properties.

00:15:18.840 --> 00:15:22.590
And we published this about
three years ago in Delft

00:15:22.590 --> 00:15:25.180
at the CESUN Conference.

00:15:25.180 --> 00:15:29.410
So the background on
here is the following,

00:15:29.410 --> 00:15:33.600
is that as you've seen,
complex engineering systems

00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:34.900
live for decades--

00:15:34.900 --> 00:15:36.660
some of them even
for centuries--

00:15:36.660 --> 00:15:39.330
and the ilities--
by ilities, we mean

00:15:39.330 --> 00:15:43.380
properties of systems that
are not the primary functional

00:15:43.380 --> 00:15:44.209
properties.

00:15:44.209 --> 00:15:45.750
In software engineering
they're often

00:15:45.750 --> 00:15:47.880
called nonfunctional properties.

00:15:47.880 --> 00:15:50.700
And the thing that's
tricky about the ilities

00:15:50.700 --> 00:15:54.660
is that you often only can
observe them during operations.

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:57.360
So you know, you can test
systems in the short term,

00:15:57.360 --> 00:15:59.560
you can see does it work?

00:15:59.560 --> 00:16:00.930
Does it fulfill its function?

00:16:00.930 --> 00:16:03.660
But whether certain
ilities are present,

00:16:03.660 --> 00:16:07.800
it often only shows
itself over time.

00:16:07.800 --> 00:16:12.450
And so most of the
research that's been done

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:14.850
and sort of quantifying
the ilities,

00:16:14.850 --> 00:16:17.610
has been looking at these
properties one at a time.

00:16:17.610 --> 00:16:20.340
So the questions we
wanted to go here,

00:16:20.340 --> 00:16:25.260
wanted to answer is, which
of these lifecycle properties

00:16:25.260 --> 00:16:27.210
are more prevalent than others?

00:16:27.210 --> 00:16:28.680
You know, the top 20.

00:16:28.680 --> 00:16:30.630
And then especially,
what's the relationship

00:16:30.630 --> 00:16:32.010
among lifecycle properties?

00:16:32.010 --> 00:16:34.650
Do they form what we
call semantic sets?

00:16:34.650 --> 00:16:37.680
And then how could you
use this information?

00:16:37.680 --> 00:16:39.840
And so here, we're
going to do this

00:16:39.840 --> 00:16:41.650
using two different methods.

00:16:41.650 --> 00:16:45.060
The first method is what I
call prevalence analysis.

00:16:45.060 --> 00:16:47.910
We're going to look in the
literature and on the internet,

00:16:47.910 --> 00:16:51.390
how frequently these
lifecycle properties show up,

00:16:51.390 --> 00:16:53.890
are mentioned, how much
we know about them.

00:16:53.890 --> 00:16:56.610
And then the second method
is a cognitive method.

00:16:56.610 --> 00:17:00.450
Where we ask people to
give their understanding

00:17:00.450 --> 00:17:04.589
of the lifecycle properties
and put them into a hierarchy,

00:17:04.589 --> 00:17:07.240
and then we'll
compare the results.

00:17:07.240 --> 00:17:10.500
So here are
essentially the results

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:12.329
from the prevalence analysis.

00:17:12.329 --> 00:17:17.490
And this is ranked according to
the number of journal articles.

00:17:17.490 --> 00:17:20.520
This is scientific
papers written,

00:17:20.520 --> 00:17:24.480
where this particular key word,
by quality or reliability,

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:28.470
shows up in the title or in
the abstract of the paper.

00:17:28.470 --> 00:17:30.800
And you can see this is
in units of thousands.

00:17:30.800 --> 00:17:31.530
OK?

00:17:31.530 --> 00:17:34.590
So quality is number one.

00:17:34.590 --> 00:17:35.310
Right?

00:17:35.310 --> 00:17:36.720
Quality is number one.

00:17:36.720 --> 00:17:40.110
The most scientific papers
are written about quality.

00:17:40.110 --> 00:17:43.380
And you can see, it's almost
a million journal articles.

00:17:43.380 --> 00:17:45.480
This is-- I'll show
this to you over time,

00:17:45.480 --> 00:17:49.170
but since 1884 is
the first year.

00:17:49.170 --> 00:17:52.710
And the databases that we
use for this are called it's

00:17:52.710 --> 00:17:54.961
Compendex and Inspect.

00:17:54.961 --> 00:17:56.460
These are actually
combined-- if you

00:17:56.460 --> 00:17:59.550
go to a website called
engineeringvillage.com,

00:17:59.550 --> 00:18:04.680
this is sort of a master
database for scientific papers

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:06.320
and engineering.

00:18:06.320 --> 00:18:08.460
That was the basis for this.

00:18:08.460 --> 00:18:10.650
Number two, reliability.

00:18:10.650 --> 00:18:12.270
Number three, safety.

00:18:12.270 --> 00:18:15.730
Then flexibility,
robustness, and so forth.

00:18:15.730 --> 00:18:21.120
And the other bar, the gray bar,
is if you Google essentially

00:18:21.120 --> 00:18:25.530
for this particular keyword
and-- you know, keep in mind,

00:18:25.530 --> 00:18:27.750
this was done about
five years ago--

00:18:27.750 --> 00:18:30.150
this is the number--
the millions of hits

00:18:30.150 --> 00:18:31.380
that you will get.

00:18:31.380 --> 00:18:34.830
And, so you know,
there's a factor

00:18:34.830 --> 00:18:37.890
of 1,000 difference here
between journal articles

00:18:37.890 --> 00:18:39.420
and hits on internet.

00:18:39.420 --> 00:18:42.650
But still, you can sort
of compare the two.

00:18:42.650 --> 00:18:46.710
And so, in some
sense, the black bar

00:18:46.710 --> 00:18:49.890
is the totality of
scientific knowledge

00:18:49.890 --> 00:18:51.900
about this lifecycle property.

00:18:51.900 --> 00:18:56.390
And then the gray bar would
be the amount of information

00:18:56.390 --> 00:18:57.090
or uses--

00:18:57.090 --> 00:18:59.130
usage of that knowledge,
at least as far

00:18:59.130 --> 00:19:01.410
as it's represented
on the internet.

00:19:01.410 --> 00:19:04.030
And what's interesting
is, in some cases

00:19:04.030 --> 00:19:10.260
the black bar is smaller
than the gray bar, which

00:19:10.260 --> 00:19:12.600
means that common
usage is [? leading. ?]

00:19:12.600 --> 00:19:15.210
So sustainability
would be an example.

00:19:15.210 --> 00:19:17.340
Everybody talks
about sustainability,

00:19:17.340 --> 00:19:18.900
companies have--

00:19:18.900 --> 00:19:21.660
they say, our system is
sustainable because, you know,

00:19:21.660 --> 00:19:25.200
it uses less resources, it
produces less emissions.

00:19:25.200 --> 00:19:28.800
But the actual amount
of scientific knowledge,

00:19:28.800 --> 00:19:31.530
the actual amount of
research as to what

00:19:31.530 --> 00:19:34.650
really is sustainability and
how do you design for it,

00:19:34.650 --> 00:19:37.642
is actually smaller
than the usage.

00:19:37.642 --> 00:19:39.600
And then there's areas
where it's the opposite.

00:19:39.600 --> 00:19:41.260
Like for example, modularity.

00:19:41.260 --> 00:19:41.760
Right?

00:19:41.760 --> 00:19:44.040
You see that in modularity.

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:46.650
So in the relative sense,
academic interest is leading.

00:19:46.650 --> 00:19:50.280
We see there's quite a lot
of literature on modularity.

00:19:50.280 --> 00:19:53.040
In mathematics, you know,
modularity and software,

00:19:53.040 --> 00:19:55.770
modularity and design,
but most people--

00:19:55.770 --> 00:19:59.010
you know, modularity per
se is not so interesting

00:19:59.010 --> 00:20:01.990
and so exciting to
the general public.

00:20:01.990 --> 00:20:04.890
So keep in mind that
for some ilities,

00:20:04.890 --> 00:20:06.510
there's an imbalance
essentially,

00:20:06.510 --> 00:20:09.189
between our understanding of--

00:20:09.189 --> 00:20:10.980
the scientific knowledge,
our understanding

00:20:10.980 --> 00:20:14.040
to be design, how to design
for it, and you know,

00:20:14.040 --> 00:20:16.440
how frequently at least
a keyword is used.

00:20:19.290 --> 00:20:21.720
Now here, this is
a little bit more--

00:20:21.720 --> 00:20:23.700
this is a little
bit harder to see.

00:20:23.700 --> 00:20:27.850
This is essentially looking
at these lifecycle properties

00:20:27.850 --> 00:20:29.980
over time.

00:20:29.980 --> 00:20:32.220
So what this graph
those you know

00:20:32.220 --> 00:20:37.980
is starting here in 1884,
cumulatively the number

00:20:37.980 --> 00:20:42.690
of journal articles published
about each lifecycle property.

00:20:42.690 --> 00:20:45.780
And roughly what way
you can think about this

00:20:45.780 --> 00:20:49.710
is that there's some lifecycle
property, the top four--

00:20:49.710 --> 00:20:53.490
five that we've been actually
working on for a long time.

00:20:53.490 --> 00:20:56.940
Even safety, you know, there's
some interesting articles

00:20:56.940 --> 00:21:01.680
in the 1890s about safety
for example, in mines.

00:21:01.680 --> 00:21:03.870
You know, coal mines.

00:21:03.870 --> 00:21:05.790
There's an article
about how does

00:21:05.790 --> 00:21:09.360
the impact of lighting--
better lighting-- on safety

00:21:09.360 --> 00:21:12.660
and productivity in 1890.

00:21:12.660 --> 00:21:15.420
And so they show that just
providing better lighting,

00:21:15.420 --> 00:21:18.280
actually has a dual
benefit; fewer accidents,

00:21:18.280 --> 00:21:21.340
fewer fatalities, and
better production output.

00:21:21.340 --> 00:21:25.170
And so that's-- and this was a
scientific study that was done

00:21:25.170 --> 00:21:29.040
by comparing data in different
mines and actually performing

00:21:29.040 --> 00:21:31.890
some experiments.

00:21:31.890 --> 00:21:35.070
Then you have a group
of life cycle properties

00:21:35.070 --> 00:21:38.310
that we only started really
thinking about and publishing

00:21:38.310 --> 00:21:41.010
about I would say,
around World War Two.

00:21:41.010 --> 00:21:44.400
Such as usability,
maintainability,

00:21:44.400 --> 00:21:48.330
and my interpretation of
this is that especially

00:21:48.330 --> 00:21:53.180
during World War Two, a big
difference made logistics.

00:21:53.180 --> 00:21:57.360
How easy was it was it
to use different weapons?

00:21:57.360 --> 00:22:00.180
How easy was it to
maintain equipment?

00:22:00.180 --> 00:22:02.730
It became a huge
determining factor

00:22:02.730 --> 00:22:04.050
in the outcome of the war.

00:22:04.050 --> 00:22:06.780
You know, for example, in North
Africa in the North African

00:22:06.780 --> 00:22:13.560
theater, you know tanks, trucks
being exposed to the sand

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:14.320
and so forth.

00:22:14.320 --> 00:22:16.290
So people really
started thinking

00:22:16.290 --> 00:22:18.330
about the military,
started thinking heavily

00:22:18.330 --> 00:22:21.300
about the importance
of maintainability

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:23.310
in the design of these systems.

00:22:23.310 --> 00:22:28.020
And after the war then, a lot
of these concepts like usability

00:22:28.020 --> 00:22:30.600
and maintainability
started spreading

00:22:30.600 --> 00:22:34.410
into general civilian life
and products and so forth.

00:22:37.980 --> 00:22:41.310
The third type of ilities
are the newer ones

00:22:41.310 --> 00:22:44.580
that we've done research
on just since the 70s,

00:22:44.580 --> 00:22:46.240
in the last 30 years.

00:22:46.240 --> 00:22:48.210
So here in this category
I would put things

00:22:48.210 --> 00:22:52.920
like sustainability,
recyclability, evolvability,

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:56.010
even interoperability-- which
means the ability of systems

00:22:56.010 --> 00:22:59.790
to connect together and work
across system boundaries.

00:22:59.790 --> 00:23:02.820
Those are pretty recent
lifecycle properties

00:23:02.820 --> 00:23:06.350
and we're still actively
researching them.

00:23:06.350 --> 00:23:11.610
So another way to show this is
by essentially making a network

00:23:11.610 --> 00:23:13.800
of these lifecycle properties.

00:23:13.800 --> 00:23:17.690
And so the way-- this is still
all using this prevalence data.

00:23:17.690 --> 00:23:21.390
Essentially what you see
here is a network diagram

00:23:21.390 --> 00:23:24.030
that has these lifecycle
properties in a network

00:23:24.030 --> 00:23:25.360
relationship.

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:29.370
Let me just explain, so
the size of the nodes

00:23:29.370 --> 00:23:32.580
relates to how much
knowledge we have.

00:23:32.580 --> 00:23:35.730
Essentially the height of
the bars that we saw earlier.

00:23:35.730 --> 00:23:38.700
And then the strength
the thickness of the line

00:23:38.700 --> 00:23:40.890
relates to the
strength of-- really

00:23:40.890 --> 00:23:43.890
how closely are these
two ilities related.

00:23:43.890 --> 00:23:45.570
And the way this
is calculated it

00:23:45.570 --> 00:23:48.750
is using the so-called
2-tuple correlation.

00:23:48.750 --> 00:23:51.900
So you take, essentially,
articles that have--

00:23:51.900 --> 00:23:55.050
you look at articles that
have, for example reliability

00:23:55.050 --> 00:23:58.440
and maintainability
in the same article.

00:23:58.440 --> 00:23:59.070
Right?

00:23:59.070 --> 00:24:00.960
And then you divide
that by the total number

00:24:00.960 --> 00:24:05.250
of articles on reliability
and or maintainability.

00:24:05.250 --> 00:24:07.410
And that's a ratio
between 0 and 1.

00:24:07.410 --> 00:24:10.815
And then this graph was produced
with a cutoff strength of so.

00:24:10.815 --> 00:24:12.030
1, right?

00:24:12.030 --> 00:24:15.600
So if there's more
than 10% of articles

00:24:15.600 --> 00:24:18.670
list these two
properties together,

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:20.760
then there will be a line here.

00:24:20.760 --> 00:24:23.160
And the stronger the line,
the thicker the line is,

00:24:23.160 --> 00:24:26.280
the more closely, the
more often these concepts

00:24:26.280 --> 00:24:28.890
are mentioned in
the same article

00:24:28.890 --> 00:24:30.100
or the same piece of work.

00:24:30.100 --> 00:24:33.780
So that reflects the
strength of relationship.

00:24:33.780 --> 00:24:38.160
Now, what's interesting is
when you first look at this,

00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:39.566
you don't see much.

00:24:39.566 --> 00:24:41.190
But after you look
at this for a while,

00:24:41.190 --> 00:24:43.330
you start to realize
a few things.

00:24:43.330 --> 00:24:45.960
First of all, in the
center of the graph

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:48.690
we have the classic
ilities of engineering.

00:24:48.690 --> 00:24:53.250
Quality, safety, reliability,
and I would argue flexibility

00:24:53.250 --> 00:24:53.920
as well.

00:24:53.920 --> 00:24:56.410
Those are the top four
that we saw before.

00:24:56.410 --> 00:24:58.560
And then around the
periphery of the graph,

00:24:58.560 --> 00:25:01.980
we have lifecycle properties
that are more recent.

00:25:01.980 --> 00:25:05.550
We haven't really thought
about them too much,

00:25:05.550 --> 00:25:09.120
we don't fully know how
to design for them yet.

00:25:09.120 --> 00:25:10.930
And if you look
at them in groups,

00:25:10.930 --> 00:25:13.630
I will argue that there are
three major groups here.

00:25:13.630 --> 00:25:15.990
So the first group
in the upper left

00:25:15.990 --> 00:25:21.280
is things like maintainability,
durability, reliability,

00:25:21.280 --> 00:25:24.230
quality, and so forth.

00:25:24.230 --> 00:25:26.870
So this is all about,
is the system made well,

00:25:26.870 --> 00:25:29.780
with high quality,
particularly early in its life.

00:25:29.780 --> 00:25:31.420
Right?

00:25:31.420 --> 00:25:36.670
Then we have a group here on
the right, and this is about,

00:25:36.670 --> 00:25:39.000
is the system easy to change.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:42.850
Is it easy to change the system
configuration-- flexibility,

00:25:42.850 --> 00:25:49.930
extensibility, modularity and
scalability, interoperability.

00:25:49.930 --> 00:25:53.410
Those are all different
sub-flavors, if you want,

00:25:53.410 --> 00:25:57.490
of being able to modify
the system over its life.

00:25:57.490 --> 00:26:01.180
And so that's a group of
ilities that that goes together.

00:26:01.180 --> 00:26:05.260
And then the third one is
resilience, robustness,

00:26:05.260 --> 00:26:08.920
quality, safety.

00:26:08.920 --> 00:26:11.950
And so this is really
related to performance

00:26:11.950 --> 00:26:14.800
of the system under different
types of uncertainty.

00:26:14.800 --> 00:26:17.410
You know, either
environmental variability

00:26:17.410 --> 00:26:21.640
or failures in the system,
and the ability of the system

00:26:21.640 --> 00:26:24.330
to withstand, or
at least perform--

00:26:24.330 --> 00:26:26.260
you know, have good
residual performance

00:26:26.260 --> 00:26:28.600
even in the face of failures.

00:26:28.600 --> 00:26:32.740
So that's, I think, an
important way to think about it.

00:26:32.740 --> 00:26:35.080
And when you're writing
requirements for systems--

00:26:35.080 --> 00:26:37.180
like the system
should be resilient.

00:26:37.180 --> 00:26:39.010
Then this helps
understand well, what

00:26:39.010 --> 00:26:41.560
