PROFESSOR: OK, good.

00:29:28.630 --> 00:29:30.760
Let me talk about the
[? message ?] too.

00:29:30.760 --> 00:29:35.590
So this was basically trying
to get to-- how do people,

00:29:35.590 --> 00:29:36.790
how do humans--

00:29:36.790 --> 00:29:39.471
there's semantics, semantics
means the meaning of words,

00:29:39.471 --> 00:29:39.970
right?

00:29:39.970 --> 00:29:44.000
Semantics is the science
of the meaning of words.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:48.060
How do they interpret
these lifecycle properties?

00:29:48.060 --> 00:29:51.580
And so humans have a
deep and possibly varied

00:29:51.580 --> 00:29:55.180
understanding of the semantics
of these lifecycle properties.

00:29:55.180 --> 00:29:59.050
So what was done here was
that a list of 15 life cycle

00:29:59.050 --> 00:30:02.230
properties, many of them are
overlapping with the ones you

00:30:02.230 --> 00:30:08.750
saw earlier, were presented
and then the challenge was to--

00:30:08.750 --> 00:30:12.650
the question that
these four groups--

00:30:12.650 --> 00:30:15.050
12 participants, four groups--

00:30:15.050 --> 00:30:17.810
had to say, is there
a hierarchy here?

00:30:17.810 --> 00:30:21.590
Are some higher level lifecycle
properties are some of them

00:30:21.590 --> 00:30:23.690
lower level properties
that support these.

00:30:23.690 --> 00:30:27.410
So there was a round one, find
the parent-child relationships,

00:30:27.410 --> 00:30:28.670
describe these.

00:30:28.670 --> 00:30:31.260
Interviews, and then
the second round.

00:30:31.260 --> 00:30:38.390
So here's essentially what was
the results of the first round.

00:30:38.390 --> 00:30:41.120
So four different
groups, so each of them

00:30:41.120 --> 00:30:45.530
basically came up with its
own version of a hierarchy.

00:30:45.530 --> 00:30:47.030
They didn't talk
to each other, they

00:30:47.030 --> 00:30:48.980
were firewalled from each other.

00:30:48.980 --> 00:30:52.700
And in all cases this
notion of value robustness

00:30:52.700 --> 00:30:53.540
came out on top.

00:30:53.540 --> 00:30:57.470
So value robustness means the
system should deliver value,

00:30:57.470 --> 00:30:59.300
right, to the stakeholders.

00:30:59.300 --> 00:31:03.490
Despite failures you know,
environmental changes,

00:31:03.490 --> 00:31:07.190
so value delivery of the system
is the top, the most important

00:31:07.190 --> 00:31:07.860
thing.

00:31:07.860 --> 00:31:12.240
Then what's different here
is how do you achieve that?

00:31:12.240 --> 00:31:14.750
So for example, you
see group one had

00:31:14.750 --> 00:31:17.870
robustness and changeability.

00:31:17.870 --> 00:31:20.060
So robustness
typically means even

00:31:20.060 --> 00:31:23.230
if you don't make any changes to
the system, it should continue,

00:31:23.230 --> 00:31:24.900
you know, it should
be survivable.

00:31:24.900 --> 00:31:26.960
It should be versatile.

00:31:26.960 --> 00:31:29.000
Changeable means
you actually modify

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:30.860
the system over its life.

00:31:30.860 --> 00:31:33.530
And then we have lower level
properties like modularity

00:31:33.530 --> 00:31:34.880
or reconfigurability.

00:31:34.880 --> 00:31:37.760
And you know, there were
differences between the groups

00:31:37.760 --> 00:31:42.270
but not as big as
you might think.

00:31:42.270 --> 00:31:46.070
So in the second round, as a
result of the second round,

00:31:46.070 --> 00:31:51.020
then this so-called means to
end hierarchy was constructed.

00:31:51.020 --> 00:31:54.440
So means means, you know, these
are the enabling lifecycle

00:31:54.440 --> 00:31:57.470
properties and ends means this
is the final, sort of this

00:31:57.470 --> 00:31:59.730
is really what you
want to achieve.

00:31:59.730 --> 00:32:02.010
And so this was
the result of that.

00:32:02.010 --> 00:32:04.190
So again, at the top
we have this notion

00:32:04.190 --> 00:32:06.020
of value robustness.

00:32:06.020 --> 00:32:08.030
And this is achieved
by a combination

00:32:08.030 --> 00:32:11.900
of survivability robustness
and changeability.

00:32:11.900 --> 00:32:15.020
And then these, in turn,
are achieved by lower level

00:32:15.020 --> 00:32:16.610
lifecycle properties.

00:32:16.610 --> 00:32:18.830
And then at the
lowest level we have

00:32:18.830 --> 00:32:22.340
things like
interoperability, modularity,

00:32:22.340 --> 00:32:25.410
reconfigurability, and so forth.

00:32:25.410 --> 00:32:28.070
And the difference
between the solid lines

00:32:28.070 --> 00:32:32.420
and the dashed lines here
is that if it's a solid line

00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:35.490
and these are
directed arrows, that

00:32:35.490 --> 00:32:40.930
means that three or four
out of four groups, right?

00:32:40.930 --> 00:32:43.230
So the majority
of groups had this

00:32:43.230 --> 00:32:46.110
is a particular
parent-child relationship.

00:32:46.110 --> 00:32:49.120
And if it's a dashed line it
means only two out of four.

00:32:49.120 --> 00:32:51.850
And if it's only one out
of 4, it's not shown here.

00:32:51.850 --> 00:32:52.350
OK?

00:32:52.350 --> 00:32:57.660
So this is kind of a combined
result across the four groups.

00:32:57.660 --> 00:33:01.290
So you know, what can
we take from this?

00:33:01.290 --> 00:33:03.420
So first of all,
lifecycle properties

00:33:03.420 --> 00:33:05.460
are absolutely critical.

00:33:05.460 --> 00:33:08.760
You'll find us in
mission statements,

00:33:08.760 --> 00:33:11.050
you know, you'll find it
in even in advertising.

00:33:11.050 --> 00:33:11.550
Right?

00:33:11.550 --> 00:33:14.640
A lot of companies say we have
we have a robust solution,

00:33:14.640 --> 00:33:18.420
we have a sustainable system,
we have resilient networks.

00:33:18.420 --> 00:33:21.870
So it really is a huge,
huge selling point.

00:33:21.870 --> 00:33:23.580
It's very critical.

00:33:23.580 --> 00:33:25.740
What I encourage you to
do as system engineers is

00:33:25.740 --> 00:33:29.520
take a critical look at this
and say, well how resilient

00:33:29.520 --> 00:33:30.240
is resilient?

00:33:30.240 --> 00:33:34.440
You know, how many subsequent
failures of the system

00:33:34.440 --> 00:33:36.000
can you tolerate?

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:37.590
Sustainability;
what does that mean

00:33:37.590 --> 00:33:42.130
in terms of kilowatt
hours per hour of usage?

00:33:42.130 --> 00:33:43.860
You have to get
down to the details

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:46.710
to start quantifying what
these lifecycle properties mean

00:33:46.710 --> 00:33:50.410
and compare them among systems.

00:33:50.410 --> 00:33:54.120
Despite differences, the two
methods that we just looked

00:33:54.120 --> 00:33:57.210
at-- so one is the prevalence
analysis and the other one is

00:33:57.210 --> 00:34:01.410
the human semantic exercise--

00:34:01.410 --> 00:34:05.170
despite differences, the high
level conclusions were similar.

00:34:05.170 --> 00:34:08.489
So some ilities are closely
related to each other and form

00:34:08.489 --> 00:34:11.989
semantic sets, meaning
they're tied together by both

00:34:11.989 --> 00:34:15.050
[? synonymie ?] or
polysemi relationships.

00:34:15.050 --> 00:34:17.736
[? Synonymie ?] means they
essentially mean the same--

00:34:17.736 --> 00:34:19.860
they're synonymous-- they
essentially mean the same

00:34:19.860 --> 00:34:20.820
thing.

00:34:20.820 --> 00:34:23.969
polysemi means-- it
is one word, but it

00:34:23.969 --> 00:34:26.790
means you can have
possible sub meanings.

00:34:26.790 --> 00:34:27.480
Right?

00:34:27.480 --> 00:34:31.320
So the idea of groups
of semantic sets.

00:34:31.320 --> 00:34:37.800
And those groups
essentially are robustness--

00:34:37.800 --> 00:34:39.989
so this is the
ability of the system

00:34:39.989 --> 00:34:44.670
to perform its job despite
either internal or exogenous

00:34:44.670 --> 00:34:45.429
disturbances.

00:34:45.429 --> 00:34:45.929
Right?

00:34:45.929 --> 00:34:47.489
That's robustness.

00:34:47.489 --> 00:34:52.110
Flexible or changeable,
which means that you

00:34:52.110 --> 00:34:54.330
can modify the system easily.

00:34:54.330 --> 00:34:56.370
You know, if you operate
the system for a while

00:34:56.370 --> 00:34:59.070
and then you realize,
Ah, I need the system

00:34:59.070 --> 00:35:00.110
to do something else.

00:35:00.110 --> 00:35:03.270
Or I need to adapt it, or make
it bigger, or make it smaller,

00:35:03.270 --> 00:35:04.890
or add some function.

00:35:04.890 --> 00:35:06.930
So you would modify
the system and that's

00:35:06.930 --> 00:35:09.420
flexibility or changeability.

00:35:09.420 --> 00:35:12.750
And then resilient
and survivable

00:35:12.750 --> 00:35:16.080
is very specifically the
ability of this system

00:35:16.080 --> 00:35:20.400
to continue performing
despite failures or attacks.

00:35:20.400 --> 00:35:20.910
Right?

00:35:20.910 --> 00:35:23.220
That's what resilience
really means.

00:35:23.220 --> 00:35:27.420
And so those seem to be the big
three semantic clusters that we

00:35:27.420 --> 00:35:29.620
see in life cycle properties.

00:35:29.620 --> 00:35:31.530
And then the third
point here is there

00:35:31.530 --> 00:35:35.160
appears to be a hierarchy of
life cycle properties with two

00:35:35.160 --> 00:35:36.510
or three levels.

00:35:36.510 --> 00:35:39.150
Where we have the lower
level properties of systems

00:35:39.150 --> 00:35:41.290
like modularity, for example.

00:35:41.290 --> 00:35:43.350
Really your customer
probably does not

00:35:43.350 --> 00:35:45.480
care about modularity, right?

00:35:45.480 --> 00:35:49.200
If you advertise the
modularity of the product, some

00:35:49.200 --> 00:35:52.620
of the more educated, some
of the more technically

00:35:52.620 --> 00:35:55.830
savvy customers, they may
understand what that means.

00:35:55.830 --> 00:35:57.210
But most of your
customers really

00:35:57.210 --> 00:35:59.430
won't appreciate
modularity because it's

00:35:59.430 --> 00:36:02.400
kind of a low level
form-oriented technical

00:36:02.400 --> 00:36:04.300
property of the system.

00:36:04.300 --> 00:36:07.110
But what they will appreciate
is the ability of the system

00:36:07.110 --> 00:36:11.670
to be reconfigured or
adaptive for different pieces,

00:36:11.670 --> 00:36:14.460
so interoperability,
modularity, et cetera

00:36:14.460 --> 00:36:17.910
are low level
lifecycle properties

00:36:17.910 --> 00:36:22.500
that act as enablers of a higher
level lifecycle properties.

00:36:22.500 --> 00:36:24.480
And so future work--

00:36:24.480 --> 00:36:27.970
future work in this
area is to both just

00:36:27.970 --> 00:36:30.570
to apply these methods
to a broader set

00:36:30.570 --> 00:36:34.410
abilities, larger group of
test subjects and more data,

00:36:34.410 --> 00:36:36.900
but also from a
practical standpoint

00:36:36.900 --> 00:36:40.060
to operationalize better.

00:36:40.060 --> 00:36:41.600
How do we write requirements?

00:36:41.600 --> 00:36:44.460
How do we actually design
for the lifecycle properties

00:36:44.460 --> 00:36:47.910
like resilience,
flexibility, changeability.

00:36:47.910 --> 00:36:49.080
How do you really design it?

00:36:49.080 --> 00:36:53.540
So go from the keyword
to real engineering

00:36:53.540 --> 00:36:57.870
by operationalizing the
sub-attributes or factors

00:36:57.870 --> 00:36:59.360
in the system.

00:36:59.360 --> 00:37:00.130
OK?

