00:50:24.260 --> 00:50:29.030
The key question here
is how expensive is it--

00:50:29.030 --> 00:50:30.710
what's the cost,
and then what is

00:50:30.710 --> 00:50:33.560
the price that you can charge
for one minute of service,

00:50:33.560 --> 00:50:34.060
right?

00:50:34.060 --> 00:50:37.030
One minute, one unit of service.

00:50:37.030 --> 00:50:39.780
And so look at
this equation here.

00:50:39.780 --> 00:50:43.800
This is CPF, stands
for cost per function.

00:50:43.800 --> 00:50:47.690
And so in the numerator we
have the lifecycle cost, which

00:50:47.690 --> 00:50:50.490
is your initial investment.

00:50:50.490 --> 00:50:52.820
And then we will
essentially capitalize

00:50:52.820 --> 00:50:55.160
that with some interest rate k.

00:50:55.160 --> 00:50:57.410
Plus then, for each
year of operation,

00:50:57.410 --> 00:51:00.590
you have the operational costs
for that year you have to add.

00:51:00.590 --> 00:51:01.700
So that's your initial--

00:51:01.700 --> 00:51:04.790
that's your development costs,
your manufacturing costs

00:51:04.790 --> 00:51:08.540
for the satellite,
including the launch costs.

00:51:08.540 --> 00:51:11.750
And then the ops costs would be
operating your ground stations,

00:51:11.750 --> 00:51:14.380
your networks, any
replenishment costs,

00:51:14.380 --> 00:51:16.550
they would be in your ops costs.

00:51:16.550 --> 00:51:18.380
And then you divide
this by what's

00:51:18.380 --> 00:51:21.219
called here the number
of billable minutes.

00:51:21.219 --> 00:51:23.510
That doesn't mean you're
actually going to bill people,

00:51:23.510 --> 00:51:27.150
it means just they are
potentially billable minutes.

00:51:27.150 --> 00:51:28.910
So that's the capacity
of the system,

00:51:28.910 --> 00:51:32.930
[? see ?] the best times
you know, 365 days,

00:51:32.930 --> 00:51:35.330
times 24 hours,
times 60 minutes,

00:51:35.330 --> 00:51:37.780
times what's the load factor.

00:51:37.780 --> 00:51:39.320
So the load factor
is essentially

00:51:39.320 --> 00:51:44.090
the capacity utilization of
the system that you anticipate.

00:51:44.090 --> 00:51:44.930
OK.

00:51:44.930 --> 00:51:48.560
So that's the basic
equation for calculating

00:51:48.560 --> 00:51:50.210
CPF, cost per function.

