00:53:09.520 --> 00:53:12.474
should be 1,000 or 2,000.

00:53:12.474 --> 00:53:14.140
And if they all show
up at the same time

00:53:14.140 --> 00:53:15.610
you're in big trouble, right?

00:53:15.610 --> 00:53:19.240
So that's the difference
between number of users

00:53:19.240 --> 00:53:21.280
or the number of
subscribers and number

00:53:21.280 --> 00:53:24.280
of active users
at any given time.

00:53:24.280 --> 00:53:28.730
That's a big part of managing
these kind of systems.

00:53:28.730 --> 00:53:32.520
However, what actually happened
is the number of actual users

00:53:32.520 --> 00:53:34.250
grew much slower.

00:53:34.250 --> 00:53:36.700
So if you plug-in some
different numbers,

00:53:36.700 --> 00:53:38.890
let's keep all the
numbers the same,

00:53:38.890 --> 00:53:43.000
except for the subscriber
base-- the number of users.

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:47.030
In this case we're going to
assume 50,000 users instead of

00:53:47.030 --> 00:53:48.010
the three million.

00:53:48.010 --> 00:53:51.010
This is closer to what
they had after about

00:53:51.010 --> 00:53:52.240
a year of operation.

00:53:52.240 --> 00:53:55.400
Now your CPF goes
to $12 per minute,

00:53:55.400 --> 00:53:57.490
which is noncompetitive.

00:53:57.490 --> 00:53:58.030
Right?

00:53:58.030 --> 00:54:04.030
Except for some extremely, like,
military applications or making

00:54:04.030 --> 00:54:07.420
some emergency phone
calls on an oil rig,

00:54:07.420 --> 00:54:08.800
you know, on the ocean.

00:54:08.800 --> 00:54:11.320
Most people at the time--

00:54:11.320 --> 00:54:12.700
now and at that time--

00:54:12.700 --> 00:54:17.920
would never pay that for
one minute of service.

00:54:17.920 --> 00:54:20.980
And so that was the
fundamental problem,

00:54:20.980 --> 00:54:25.240
is that the user base did not
materialize as fast as planned.

00:54:25.240 --> 00:54:28.210
Therefore this cost per
function was way higher

00:54:28.210 --> 00:54:31.510
and they did charge,
you know, $3 to $5

00:54:31.510 --> 00:54:34.930
per minute of usage
of the system, which

00:54:34.930 --> 00:54:38.920
as you try to squeeze
your existing users more,

00:54:38.920 --> 00:54:42.190
you're not going to get the ramp
up and scale up in the system

00:54:42.190 --> 00:54:42.970
that you need.

00:54:42.970 --> 00:54:46.450
That was the fundamental
problem with the economics

00:54:46.450 --> 00:54:49.490
of the system.

00:54:49.490 --> 00:54:52.790
So let me talk a little bit
about the design decisions

00:54:52.790 --> 00:54:56.740
the conceptual design of what
this design space looks like.

00:54:56.740 --> 00:55:00.160
So fundamental-- oh, the other
thing I should mention to you,

00:55:00.160 --> 00:55:04.570
what was interesting is after
the bankruptcy, both of Iridium

00:55:04.570 --> 00:55:08.020
and Globalstar, both of the
chief engineers for both

00:55:08.020 --> 00:55:12.460
of these systems
took refuge at MIT.

00:55:12.460 --> 00:55:14.050
Essentially, they came to like--

00:55:14.050 --> 00:55:17.400
Joel Schindall, who was the
chief engineer for Globalstar,

00:55:17.400 --> 00:55:21.250
great guy, both very competent
people, came to MIT--

00:55:21.250 --> 00:55:23.560
still there, still
a professor there.

00:55:23.560 --> 00:55:26.490
And then Ray Leopold was
one of the three architects

00:55:26.490 --> 00:55:29.980
for Iridium, also came
to MIT during the time.

00:55:29.980 --> 00:55:33.070
So I had extensive
discussions with them,

00:55:33.070 --> 00:55:35.890
and what you see
here on slide 25

00:55:35.890 --> 00:55:38.170
is one result of
those discussions.

00:55:38.170 --> 00:55:40.840
Which is, the key
design decisions

00:55:40.840 --> 00:55:44.800
that they have to make,
fundamentally, there is--

00:55:44.800 --> 00:55:47.050
you won't be
surprised to see this,

00:55:47.050 --> 00:55:49.930
this is the magic
number seven, right?

00:55:49.930 --> 00:55:52.030
Seven key design decisions.

00:55:52.030 --> 00:55:55.360
When you design a satellite
consultation for communication

00:55:55.360 --> 00:55:57.970
purposes, constellation type--

00:55:57.970 --> 00:56:01.330
polar or walker,
orbital altitude,

00:56:01.330 --> 00:56:03.710
minimum elevation angle
above the horizon--

00:56:03.710 --> 00:56:06.580
that you can communicate--

00:56:06.580 --> 00:56:09.820
satellite transmitting
power, the size

00:56:09.820 --> 00:56:13.100
of your primary antenna,
your multi-access scheme.

00:56:13.100 --> 00:56:17.080
So this is time division or
code division multiplexing.

00:56:17.080 --> 00:56:19.840
And then the last one is about
the network architecture--

00:56:19.840 --> 00:56:22.600
do you have inter-satellite
links, yes or no?

00:56:22.600 --> 00:56:24.640
Inter-satellite links
means satellites

00:56:24.640 --> 00:56:27.250
can talk to each other.

00:56:27.250 --> 00:56:31.210
And Iridium chose that,
Globalstar did not.

00:56:31.210 --> 00:56:34.870
So in Globalstar, the Globalstar
satellites cannot talk to each

00:56:34.870 --> 00:56:36.370
other directly in space.

00:56:36.370 --> 00:56:37.450
They can only talk--

00:56:37.450 --> 00:56:41.560
it's a bent pipe system
to a ground station.

00:56:41.560 --> 00:56:42.060
OK?

00:56:42.060 --> 00:56:45.360
So if you this is like
the morphological matrix

00:56:45.360 --> 00:56:49.350
that you learned about, you
just pick design decisions

00:56:49.350 --> 00:56:52.015
in this morphological
matrix and you come up

00:56:52.015 --> 00:56:52.890
with an architecture.

00:56:52.890 --> 00:56:56.550
In fact, a full factorial
search of the space

00:56:56.550 --> 00:57:02.370
would reveal 1,440 different
satellite architectures.

00:57:02.370 --> 00:57:05.960
So that's on the input side,
what's the output vector?

00:57:05.960 --> 00:57:09.720
What do you care about in
terms of output of the system?

00:57:09.720 --> 00:57:12.600
Well first of all, performance.

00:57:12.600 --> 00:57:16.500
So the performance-- this
is for voice communications.

00:57:16.500 --> 00:57:20.310
In a sense it applies to
data communications as well.

00:57:20.310 --> 00:57:23.070
It is your data rate
per channel, right?

00:57:23.070 --> 00:57:27.750
4.8 Kbps, your bit
error rate, like

00:57:27.750 --> 00:57:30.990
what is the average number
of bits that are wrong?

00:57:30.990 --> 00:57:32.400
10 to the minus 3.

00:57:32.400 --> 00:57:35.360
That's actually
pretty-- not a very--

00:57:35.360 --> 00:57:37.350
that's not a very
stringent requirement.

00:57:37.350 --> 00:57:40.560
And the reason is this is
for voice communication,

00:57:40.560 --> 00:57:44.280
this is not for sending, you
know, commands to a spacecraft

00:57:44.280 --> 00:57:45.200
going to Mars.

00:57:45.200 --> 00:57:49.170
If you send commands, it would
have to be 10 to the minus 10,

00:57:49.170 --> 00:57:51.060
or 10 to the minus 9.

00:57:51.060 --> 00:57:53.050
Much, much better
bit error rate.

00:57:53.050 --> 00:57:55.650
But this is OK for voice.

00:57:55.650 --> 00:57:59.220
And then the link
fading margin, 16 DB.

00:57:59.220 --> 00:58:01.570
This is the strength
of the signal, which

00:58:01.570 --> 00:58:03.420
which will dictate
whether or not

00:58:03.420 --> 00:58:07.300
you can use the phone under
trees or in buildings.

00:58:07.300 --> 00:58:09.900
So you want this number to be
higher, but the higher it is,

00:58:09.900 --> 00:58:11.490
you know given
the power you have

00:58:11.490 --> 00:58:13.860
on the satellite, the
fewer channels you have.

00:58:13.860 --> 00:58:15.270
So there's trade-offs.

00:58:15.270 --> 00:58:19.520
So what was done here is to
keep the performance foxed,

00:58:19.520 --> 00:58:22.200
and so that you can
compare architectures,

00:58:22.200 --> 00:58:24.900
compare apples to apples.

00:58:24.900 --> 00:58:26.790
Then we have capacity,
which is the number

00:58:26.790 --> 00:58:29.490
of simultaneous duplex channels.

00:58:29.490 --> 00:58:31.290
And then finally,
the lifecycle cost

00:58:31.290 --> 00:58:34.560
of the system, which includes
research development, test,

00:58:34.560 --> 00:58:38.760
and evaluation, satellite
construction and test, launch

00:58:38.760 --> 00:58:41.540
and orbital insertion,
and then the operations

00:58:41.540 --> 00:58:43.060
and replenishment.

00:58:43.060 --> 00:58:45.000
So if the satellite
fails in orbit,

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:47.820
either you have to already
have prepositioned to spare,

00:58:47.820 --> 00:58:50.310
or you're going to
launch a replacement.

00:58:50.310 --> 00:58:53.220
And this actually
happened in both cases,

00:58:53.220 --> 00:58:56.290
both constellations.

00:58:56.290 --> 00:59:00.270
So in order to then, connect
the input to the output,

00:59:00.270 --> 00:59:04.620
you need to build a simulator
or a model of this system.

00:59:04.620 --> 00:59:07.920
And this is a high-level view
of what that model looks like.

00:59:07.920 --> 00:59:11.010
So we take our input,
our design decisions,

00:59:11.010 --> 00:59:14.850
and certain constants that we
assume-- a constant vector.

00:59:14.850 --> 00:59:19.470
And cascade this information
from the constellation module,

00:59:19.470 --> 00:59:22.560
takes the altitude and the
minimum elevation angle,

00:59:22.560 --> 00:59:23.940
and produces--

00:59:23.940 --> 00:59:26.250
t is the number of
satellites and p

00:59:26.250 --> 00:59:28.710
is the number of
orbital planes, so this

00:59:28.710 --> 00:59:30.510
is sort of orbital dynamics.

00:59:30.510 --> 00:59:35.580
The spacecraft module
calculates the satellite mass,

00:59:35.580 --> 00:59:40.500
the satellite network builds
essentially the communication

00:59:40.500 --> 00:59:41.730
pathways.

00:59:41.730 --> 00:59:46.200
The link budget will calculate
the capacity of the system.

00:59:46.200 --> 00:59:48.930
You know, given those
performance constraints.

00:59:48.930 --> 00:59:52.530
The launch module will
determine how many launches

00:59:52.530 --> 00:59:54.330
do you need, from where.

00:59:54.330 --> 00:59:56.790
And then the cost module
basically calculates

00:59:56.790 --> 00:59:59.680
the total cost of the
system, the lifecycle cost,

00:59:59.680 --> 01:00:03.390
and finally you get essentially
a trade-off of lifecycle cost

01:00:03.390 --> 01:00:05.265
versus capacity of the system.

01:00:07.996 --> 01:00:09.870
Let me just show you
some, you know, you say,

01:00:09.870 --> 01:00:12.940
well that's tying together
a lot of information

01:00:12.940 --> 01:00:14.520
into a multi-disciplinary model.

01:00:14.520 --> 01:00:17.380
So what kind of
information do you have?

01:00:17.380 --> 01:00:19.540
You have a mix, really
of physics based models--

01:00:19.540 --> 01:00:22.800
so this is a very well known
equation, the eB/N0, that this

01:00:22.800 --> 01:00:25.380
is the energy bit
over noise ratio.

01:00:25.380 --> 01:00:28.890
This is a closed form
physics-based equation that

01:00:28.890 --> 01:00:31.600
tells you how much
energy is there per bit--

01:00:31.600 --> 01:00:35.010
what's the signal to noise
ratio on a per bit basis.

01:00:35.010 --> 01:00:38.580
And this is a function of
transmitter power, receiver

01:00:38.580 --> 01:00:42.000
and transmission gains,
various losses in the system.

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:43.740
And then some of the equations--

01:00:43.740 --> 01:00:45.390
some of the information
is empirical.

01:00:45.390 --> 01:00:48.300
For example, the relationship
between spacecraft

01:00:48.300 --> 01:00:50.910
[? wet ?] mass
and payload power.

01:00:50.910 --> 01:00:54.300
You know, if wanted to have
a closed form or you wanted

01:00:54.300 --> 01:00:56.700
to have more detail, you
would have to almost build

01:00:56.700 --> 01:00:58.380
a CAD model, right?

01:00:58.380 --> 01:00:59.700
A separate model.

01:00:59.700 --> 01:01:03.090
You'd have to-- for each
of the 1,440 architectures,

01:01:03.090 --> 01:01:07.740
you'd have to manually construct
an individual detailed design.

01:01:07.740 --> 01:01:10.440
And that's not feasible,
so what you do instead

01:01:10.440 --> 01:01:14.280
is you use some prior
data-- and you can see here

01:01:14.280 --> 01:01:16.650
a scaling relationship.

01:01:16.650 --> 01:01:21.180
It's not perfect, but
we have error bars,

01:01:21.180 --> 01:01:22.660
we know how good it is.

01:01:22.660 --> 01:01:25.080
Satellite mass,
satellite wet mass

01:01:25.080 --> 01:01:28.770
is a function of transmitter
power and, in this case,

01:01:28.770 --> 01:01:31.080
propellant mass.

01:01:31.080 --> 01:01:35.890
So two kinds of equations.

01:01:35.890 --> 01:01:38.110
Benchmarking.

01:01:38.110 --> 01:01:41.020
So once you have this model,
you need to ask the question,

01:01:41.020 --> 01:01:42.950
how can I trust this model?

01:01:42.950 --> 01:01:45.850
Does it give me a
reasonable answers?

01:01:45.850 --> 01:01:48.340
And in this case,
benchmarking the process

01:01:48.340 --> 01:01:50.620
of validating
simulation by comparing

01:01:50.620 --> 01:01:53.230
the predictive response
against reality.

01:01:53.230 --> 01:01:57.080
So just quickly here, showing
you four kinds of data.

01:01:57.080 --> 01:01:59.860
So one is the simultaneous
channels of the constellation,

01:01:59.860 --> 01:02:03.340
this is the prediction
of capacity.

01:02:03.340 --> 01:02:05.140
You can see it's pretty good.

01:02:05.140 --> 01:02:08.080
In this case, the model is
actually a little conservative.

01:02:08.080 --> 01:02:11.530
So the blue bars are the
actual planned capacities.

01:02:11.530 --> 01:02:14.560
The red ones or
magenta is simulated,

01:02:14.560 --> 01:02:16.990
and you can see that the
simulation under-predicts,

01:02:16.990 --> 01:02:20.450
slightly, the true
capacity of the system.

01:02:20.450 --> 01:02:24.010
Life cycle costs, you saw that
Iridium was just a bit more

01:02:24.010 --> 01:02:25.570
than $5 billion.

01:02:25.570 --> 01:02:28.870
Globalstar was between $3
million and $4 million.

01:02:28.870 --> 01:02:32.080
And so here we're in
the right ballpark.

01:02:32.080 --> 01:02:34.630
And then in terms
of satellite mass

01:02:34.630 --> 01:02:38.350
and the number of satellites
in the constellation required,

01:02:38.350 --> 01:02:40.310
we matched that very closely.

01:02:40.310 --> 01:02:42.340
And the reason for
this is, fundamentally

01:02:42.340 --> 01:02:43.960
this is just geometry.

01:02:43.960 --> 01:02:44.860
Right?

01:02:44.860 --> 01:02:48.040
If I can tell you the altitude
and the minimum elevation

01:02:48.040 --> 01:02:51.280
angle, and I'm telling you I
need I need global coverage

01:02:51.280 --> 01:02:53.500
and I want dual redundancy,
so you can always

01:02:53.500 --> 01:02:56.410
see at least two
satellites, it's

01:02:56.410 --> 01:02:59.290
just geometry to be able to
figure out how many satellites

01:02:59.290 --> 01:03:01.240
and how many orbital
planes you need.

01:03:01.240 --> 01:03:03.670
And that's why the
model, or the simulation,

01:03:03.670 --> 01:03:06.280
and reality match
very, very closely.

01:03:06.280 --> 01:03:09.730
So this gives you
some confidence

01:03:09.730 --> 01:03:11.960
that this model is reasonable.

01:03:11.960 --> 01:03:15.070
So what you can
do with it is now

01:03:15.070 --> 01:03:17.020
what we call Trade
Space exploration.

01:03:17.020 --> 01:03:20.470
Which is, in a sense, what
you did for the [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:20.470 --> 01:03:21.740
competition.

01:03:21.740 --> 01:03:25.960
So this picture here, this
graph shows you the life cycle

01:03:25.960 --> 01:03:28.990
costs over those
15 years, versus

01:03:28.990 --> 01:03:31.060
global capacity of a system.

01:03:31.060 --> 01:03:33.880
Each of these blue
dots represents one

01:03:33.880 --> 01:03:36.880
of those 1,440 architectures.

01:03:36.880 --> 01:03:41.080
And you can even see on
this, where Iridium actual

01:03:41.080 --> 01:03:44.920
versus simulated falls and
where Globalstar actual

01:03:44.920 --> 01:03:46.020
versus simulated falls.

01:03:46.020 --> 01:03:49.210
So both of them were actually
off the Pareto frontier,

01:03:49.210 --> 01:03:52.540
which was interesting and
led to quite some discussion.

01:03:52.540 --> 01:03:55.790
And you can-- the
Pareto frontier itself

01:03:55.790 --> 01:03:58.240
was, of course, very useful.

01:03:58.240 --> 01:04:02.470
One of the reasons that Iridium
is not on the Pareto frontier

01:04:02.470 --> 01:04:07.126
is that fundamentally, polar
constellations are inefficient.

01:04:07.126 --> 01:04:09.250
And, if you think about
it, when the satellites are

01:04:09.250 --> 01:04:13.190
crossing over the poles, they're
very close to each other.

01:04:13.190 --> 01:04:14.670
And they're actually
not crossing

01:04:14.670 --> 01:04:17.660
exactly over the poles, or you
could actually collide, right?

01:04:17.660 --> 01:04:21.350
So you offset them slightly
to avoid collisions.

01:04:21.350 --> 01:04:25.320
But some of the
satellites actually

01:04:25.320 --> 01:04:28.170
get turned off when
they cross the poles.

01:04:28.170 --> 01:04:31.740
So you're not utilizing your
assets super efficiently

01:04:31.740 --> 01:04:33.490
in the polar constellation.

01:04:33.490 --> 01:04:36.270
Which is one of the
reasons why they are not

01:04:36.270 --> 01:04:38.130
on Pareto frontier.

01:04:38.130 --> 01:04:41.670
Now, the way you would use
this in a traditional system

01:04:41.670 --> 01:04:44.700
engineering approach, which is
traditional system engineering

01:04:44.700 --> 01:04:47.180
approach means give
me the requirement,

01:04:47.180 --> 01:04:50.595
write down the requirements,
and then find the minimum cost

01:04:50.595 --> 01:04:52.110
design for that requirement.

01:04:52.110 --> 01:04:57.750
So a requirement could be we
need a capacity of 50,000,

01:04:57.750 --> 01:05:00.780
for example, and then you
find this intersection

01:05:00.780 --> 01:05:03.690
with the Pareto
front, and that's

01:05:03.690 --> 01:05:07.440
the minimum lifecycle
cost design that

01:05:07.440 --> 01:05:08.580
gives you that capacity.

01:05:08.580 --> 01:05:09.120
Right?

01:05:09.120 --> 01:05:11.400
And that's the system
you pick, and that's

01:05:11.400 --> 01:05:12.630
what you go and build.

01:05:12.630 --> 01:05:14.430
And that's essentially
what they did.

01:05:14.430 --> 01:05:17.460
The problem with this if
there is high uncertainty

01:05:17.460 --> 01:05:21.090
is, the true requirement
is kind of unknown.

01:05:21.090 --> 01:05:24.150
The market will tell
us in the future what

01:05:24.150 --> 01:05:26.130
the true capacity should be.

01:05:26.130 --> 01:05:28.270
So how do you deal with this?

01:05:28.270 --> 01:05:30.180
Well, you could be--

01:05:30.180 --> 01:05:32.180
we're going to be on
the safe side, right?

01:05:35.730 --> 01:05:38.760
We're going to oversize--
so if the true demand,

01:05:38.760 --> 01:05:40.610
the true capacity
that you would need,

01:05:40.610 --> 01:05:42.840
is higher than
what you just had,

01:05:42.840 --> 01:05:45.810
your system is going to
be under capacity, right?

01:05:45.810 --> 01:05:47.430
Your system is going
to be undersized

01:05:47.430 --> 01:05:48.700
for what it should be.

01:05:48.700 --> 01:05:52.140
And so what happens in practice?

01:05:52.140 --> 01:05:55.493
What do you think happens in
an under capacity situation?

01:05:59.357 --> 01:06:00.323
What would you say?

01:06:05.160 --> 01:06:09.821
The system is too small relative
to the market that you're in.

01:06:13.190 --> 01:06:15.090
You're not capturing
as much as you can,

01:06:15.090 --> 01:06:17.210
meaning a competitor
will probably capture.

01:06:17.210 --> 01:06:19.970
I mean, I guess you can
change your price policy,

01:06:19.970 --> 01:06:22.370
but fundamentally,
you're missing out

01:06:22.370 --> 01:06:24.540
on market opportunity.

01:06:24.540 --> 01:06:27.230
The other situation, which
is actually what happened,

01:06:27.230 --> 01:06:31.220
is that the demand is much
less than we anticipated.

01:06:31.220 --> 01:06:33.830
Your system is
oversized and remember,

01:06:33.830 --> 01:06:36.440
once you launch a
satellite constellation,

01:06:36.440 --> 01:06:38.420
it's not like a fleet
of taxis, right?

01:06:38.420 --> 01:06:43.250
Where you just park
them in a parking lot.

01:06:43.250 --> 01:06:47.210
You've already-- the
fixed cost is very high.

01:06:47.210 --> 01:06:52.980
So if demand is below capacity,
you have all this investment

01:06:52.980 --> 01:06:55.530
here, lifecycle cost has
been wasted because you

01:06:55.530 --> 01:06:56.990
oversized the system.

01:06:56.990 --> 01:06:59.630
And the challenge is
that the true requirement

01:06:59.630 --> 01:07:02.810
is kind of like this-- there's
this probability, density

01:07:02.810 --> 01:07:03.950
function.

01:07:03.950 --> 01:07:04.720
Right?

01:07:04.720 --> 01:07:07.600
It's a probabilistic
requirement, essentially.

01:07:07.600 --> 01:07:11.120
And there's no set of
experiments because of all

01:07:11.120 --> 01:07:13.100
the [INAUDIBLE] uncertainty.

01:07:13.100 --> 01:07:15.170
It's not a systemic uncertainty.

01:07:15.170 --> 01:07:17.090
There's no set of
experiments you

01:07:17.090 --> 01:07:21.480
could do today that will help
you refine the requirements.

01:07:21.480 --> 01:07:25.670
Now they did do market studies,
but again those market studies

01:07:25.670 --> 01:07:28.990
were years ahead of when the
actual system was launched.

01:07:28.990 --> 01:07:31.310
So they were unreliable,
fundamentally.

01:07:31.310 --> 01:07:35.900
So what I'm arguing here
is in this kind of system

01:07:35.900 --> 01:07:37.316
where you have
large uncertainties

01:07:37.316 --> 01:07:40.520
as to the true requirements,
you shouldn't just

01:07:40.520 --> 01:07:43.670
guess and then put billions
of dollars on a guess.

01:07:43.670 --> 01:07:46.010
This is like playing
in the casino, right?

01:07:46.010 --> 01:07:46.970
Essentially.

01:07:46.970 --> 01:07:50.400
What you should do is think
about the problem differently.

01:07:50.400 --> 01:07:53.540
And in this case, the
answer is staged deployment,

01:07:53.540 --> 01:07:56.050
or one of the answers
is staged deployments.

01:07:56.050 --> 01:07:59.690
So you build a system such
that it can adapt itself

01:07:59.690 --> 01:08:01.130
to the uncertain demand.

01:08:01.130 --> 01:08:04.280
So you build, initially,
a smaller, more affordable

01:08:04.280 --> 01:08:04.990
system.

01:08:04.990 --> 01:08:06.890
But-- and then the
system has already

01:08:06.890 --> 01:08:10.160
built into it the
flexibility or scalability

01:08:10.160 --> 01:08:11.510
to expand if needed.

01:08:11.510 --> 01:08:13.730
But only if needed.

01:08:13.730 --> 01:08:16.979
And there are two major
economic advantages to that.

01:08:16.979 --> 01:08:20.060
One is that you don't need to
spend all the capital up front.

01:08:20.060 --> 01:08:22.729
As so you're deferring
capital investment.

01:08:22.729 --> 01:08:27.050
And you retain the decision
freedom to reconfigure or not,

01:08:27.050 --> 01:08:30.170
and that's typically what
we call the real option.

01:08:30.170 --> 01:08:34.490
You've created a real
option for the future.

01:08:34.490 --> 01:08:38.460
So the question, then, is
well how valuable is that?

01:08:38.460 --> 01:08:42.830
It is worthwhile doing this
staged deployment approach?

01:08:42.830 --> 01:08:46.130
So there's probably
different ways of doing this,

01:08:46.130 --> 01:08:47.660
and I just want to
share with you--

01:08:47.660 --> 01:08:50.010
and this is from the
paper-- how this was done.

01:08:50.010 --> 01:08:53.450
So step one is you partition
your design vector.

01:08:53.450 --> 01:08:56.600
So you basically decide
which part of the system

01:08:56.600 --> 01:08:58.790
is flexible-- because
you can't make everything

01:08:58.790 --> 01:09:01.310
flexible typically--
what part is flexible

01:09:01.310 --> 01:09:05.390
and what part is fixed, is
the base, you can't change it?

01:09:05.390 --> 01:09:08.330
So in this case
usually the idea is

01:09:08.330 --> 01:09:11.210
that the satellites
themselves, the design

01:09:11.210 --> 01:09:13.700
of the satellite, the
transmitter power,

01:09:13.700 --> 01:09:18.470
that their protocol, and
the network architecture

01:09:18.470 --> 01:09:20.330
should be fixed, right?

01:09:20.330 --> 01:09:23.370
Those things are
difficult to change.

01:09:23.370 --> 01:09:26.810
We're going to allow the
astrodynamics, the actual shape

01:09:26.810 --> 01:09:29.090
of the constellation,
to be flexible.

01:09:29.090 --> 01:09:30.920
So keep the satellites
the same, only

01:09:30.920 --> 01:09:33.020
change the arrangement in space.

01:09:33.020 --> 01:09:35.450
So what you do is you
partition the design vector

01:09:35.450 --> 01:09:40.180
into the flexible
and inflexible parts.

01:09:40.180 --> 01:09:43.779
And when you do this,
in step two, what's

01:09:43.779 --> 01:09:47.790
nice about this is you can
then actually find families

01:09:47.790 --> 01:09:49.569
of designs, right?

01:09:49.569 --> 01:09:53.569
You can find families
of designs where the--

01:09:53.569 --> 01:09:55.240
we have a little lag here--

01:09:55.240 --> 01:09:57.130
that you can find
families of design

01:09:57.130 --> 01:09:58.750
that share the constant parts.

01:09:58.750 --> 01:10:00.590
That have the common--

01:10:00.590 --> 01:10:03.550
So what's shown in this
graph here-- this is again,

01:10:03.550 --> 01:10:06.940
our design space, kind of
zoomed in a little bit more--

01:10:06.940 --> 01:10:10.600
every one of these points that
are connected with these lines

01:10:10.600 --> 01:10:14.580
uses the same types of
satellite [INAUDIBLE]..

01:10:14.580 --> 01:10:17.890
Same transmitter power,
same antenna diameter,

01:10:17.890 --> 01:10:20.350
and all of them have
inter-satellite links.

01:10:20.350 --> 01:10:23.780
So effectively,
you're partitioning

01:10:23.780 --> 01:10:27.580
the design say into subsets
that share common features,

01:10:27.580 --> 01:10:31.180
and then we call this
a family of designs.

01:10:31.180 --> 01:10:35.710
And the idea is to start
small, so on the left side,

01:10:35.710 --> 01:10:38.410
and then you grow the
system over time right?

01:10:38.410 --> 01:10:40.400
But only if needed.

01:10:40.400 --> 01:10:48.820
So when you do this, you 1440-
strong design space turns out

01:10:48.820 --> 01:10:52.330
to be decomposable into
40 different paths.

01:10:52.330 --> 01:10:54.940
Now, which path would
you choose here?

01:10:54.940 --> 01:10:58.630
Well you want to be as close
to the Pareto front possible.

01:10:58.630 --> 01:11:02.670
So this is an example
of all of a path.

01:11:02.670 --> 01:11:05.710
In this path, if we
started on the lower

01:11:05.710 --> 01:11:08.530
we would start
with 24 satellites

01:11:08.530 --> 01:11:13.090
and then we would actually
move them to a lower altitude.

01:11:13.090 --> 01:11:17.320
And add 30 more in
step two, and then you

01:11:17.320 --> 01:11:20.180
would gradually grow the
constellation over time.

01:11:20.180 --> 01:11:20.850
You see that?

01:11:20.850 --> 01:11:23.190
This is actually not
too different from how

01:11:23.190 --> 01:11:24.460
GPS was done, right?

01:11:24.460 --> 01:11:28.580
The GPS constellation
was deployed in phases,

01:11:28.580 --> 01:11:30.610
but it was not market
driven, it was just

01:11:30.610 --> 01:11:34.360
sort of phasing the
development for risk reduction,

01:11:34.360 --> 01:11:37.084
and spreading off the capital.

01:11:37.084 --> 01:11:38.500
The other thing
that's interesting

01:11:38.500 --> 01:11:41.650
here is that as you
grow the constellation,

01:11:41.650 --> 01:11:43.752
it moves further away.

01:11:43.752 --> 01:11:46.650
It moves further
away from the front.

01:11:46.650 --> 01:11:49.360
So when it's small, this
particular [INAUDIBLE]

01:11:49.360 --> 01:11:52.060
is close to being optimal,
and as you scale it

01:11:52.060 --> 01:11:54.230
up it becomes more sub-optimal.

01:11:54.230 --> 01:11:57.550
And there's other paths that
have the opposite behavior;

01:11:57.550 --> 01:12:00.520
where when small it's
kind of suboptimal,

01:12:00.520 --> 01:12:03.880
and as you make it bigger, it
gets closer to the optimality.

01:12:03.880 --> 01:12:05.150
Pretty interesting.

01:12:05.150 --> 01:12:09.130
So that's step two,
find the paths.

01:12:09.130 --> 01:12:13.210
Step three, you now have to
model the actual uncertainty.

01:12:13.210 --> 01:12:15.400
And in this case there
are different ways

01:12:15.400 --> 01:12:17.020
to model uncertainty.

01:12:17.020 --> 01:12:19.850
In this case, what we
used was a GBM model--

01:12:19.850 --> 01:12:21.900
geometric Brownian motion.

01:12:21.900 --> 01:12:24.670
This is well-known in
physics and applied

01:12:24.670 --> 01:12:27.530
to statistics, physics,
this has been applied

01:12:27.530 --> 01:12:29.690
to the stock market, right?

01:12:29.690 --> 01:12:32.890
And the idea here is
that in this case,

01:12:32.890 --> 01:12:35.810
the man behaves like
a particle in a fluid.

01:12:35.810 --> 01:12:36.310
Right?

01:12:36.310 --> 01:12:40.020
That's kind of moving in
an unpredictable fashion.

01:12:40.020 --> 01:12:43.210
So this is the basic
equation for-- this

01:12:43.210 --> 01:12:47.200
is a discrete version of
geometric Brownian motion,

01:12:47.200 --> 01:12:52.040
you have some trends
nu, nu times delta-t,

01:12:52.040 --> 01:12:56.350
so this is the delta and
demand, or the change in demand,

01:12:56.350 --> 01:13:00.850
divided by demand, so this is
normalized change in demand,

01:13:00.850 --> 01:13:04.450
is nu times delta-t,
so your trend times

01:13:04.450 --> 01:13:09.940
delta-t plus sigma times epsilon
times square root of delta-t.

01:13:09.940 --> 01:13:11.980
Epsilon is a standard,
normally distributed

01:13:11.980 --> 01:13:17.830
random variable between 0
and 1, and epsilon and sigma

01:13:17.830 --> 01:13:20.800
is your volatility, essentially.

01:13:20.800 --> 01:13:22.900
So here's some
examples, if you start

01:13:22.900 --> 01:13:25.660
with an initial
demand of 50,000,

01:13:25.660 --> 01:13:30.280
which is what they actually
saw as an initial demand early

01:13:30.280 --> 01:13:34.430
on, you have a growth
of about 8% per year.

01:13:34.430 --> 01:13:36.310
This is your trend.

01:13:36.310 --> 01:13:40.030
Plus in this case,
a volatility of 40%

01:13:40.030 --> 01:13:43.390
per year, which seems high
but in this kind of very

01:13:43.390 --> 01:13:46.930
new technology, new system, is
actually not that far fetched.

01:13:46.930 --> 01:13:50.440
You get three different-- these
are just three examples of how

01:13:50.440 --> 01:13:51.730
demand might evolve.

01:13:51.730 --> 01:13:53.350
These are just three scenarios.

01:13:53.350 --> 01:13:57.190
So demand can go up,
it can go down, and--

01:13:57.190 --> 01:14:00.610
GBM is very nice, but one
of the downsides of GBM

01:14:00.610 --> 01:14:04.660
is there's infinitely many
scenarios that you can generate

01:14:04.660 --> 01:14:07.090
because it's fundamentally--
even though it's

01:14:07.090 --> 01:14:11.290
discretized in time, it's not
discretized and in demand.

01:14:11.290 --> 01:14:15.520
So a simpler version of this,
a more discrete version,

01:14:15.520 --> 01:14:18.860
is a so-called
binomial lattice model.

01:14:18.860 --> 01:14:20.980
So the way this
works is again, you

01:14:20.980 --> 01:14:23.660
start with some initial
demand here on the left

01:14:23.660 --> 01:14:28.970
and then you discretize this
such that moving through time,

01:14:28.970 --> 01:14:31.720
you can look at
different scenarios.

01:14:31.720 --> 01:14:32.220
Right?

01:14:32.220 --> 01:14:36.180
These scenarios could
be-- the best scenario

01:14:36.180 --> 01:14:38.571
is things just keep growing.

01:14:38.571 --> 01:14:39.070
Right?

01:14:39.070 --> 01:14:40.900
Grow, grow, grow.

01:14:40.900 --> 01:14:43.870
Here, time, the 15 years,
have been sub-divided

01:14:43.870 --> 01:14:47.390
into five three-year periods.

01:14:47.390 --> 01:14:50.800
So here's a sample scenario,
demand goes up, goes up,

01:14:50.800 --> 01:14:52.480
and then it goes
down twice, and then

01:14:52.480 --> 01:14:54.530
it goes up again in the period.

01:14:54.530 --> 01:14:57.490
And so this is a
discretized random walk.

01:14:57.490 --> 01:15:01.960
And you can choose the numbers,
so the sigma, the volatility,

01:15:01.960 --> 01:15:05.560
the amount of the up and down
movement, and the probability,

01:15:05.560 --> 01:15:08.230
p, of going up, and then
the probability of 1

01:15:08.230 --> 01:15:10.960
minus p of going
down, are chosen such

01:15:10.960 --> 01:15:14.870
that they're consistent
with the GBM model.

01:15:14.870 --> 01:15:18.520
So this model is the
equivalent of the GBM model,

01:15:18.520 --> 01:15:19.960
it's just discretized.

01:15:19.960 --> 01:15:22.390
So the beauty of this
is that you can now

01:15:22.390 --> 01:15:25.270
simplify this to 32
different scenarios

01:15:25.270 --> 01:15:27.280
instead of infinitely many.

01:15:27.280 --> 01:15:32.390
And each of those scenarios
is not equally probable.

01:15:32.390 --> 01:15:35.410
There is actually probability
weighted scenarios,

01:15:35.410 --> 01:15:39.700
depending on what nu and
sigma are that are underlined.

01:15:39.700 --> 01:15:42.430
So now we have 40 paths, right?

01:15:42.430 --> 01:15:44.800
We have 40 evolution
paths of the system

01:15:44.800 --> 01:15:47.570
and we have 32 different
future scenarios.

01:15:47.570 --> 01:15:50.290
So what we do now in
the next step, four,

01:15:50.290 --> 01:15:53.470
is to put the two
together and calculate

01:15:53.470 --> 01:15:55.780
the cost of each path.

01:15:55.780 --> 01:15:58.060
Calculate the cost of
each path with respect

01:15:58.060 --> 01:16:00.160
to each of the demand
scenarios, look

01:16:00.160 --> 01:16:04.840
at the weighted average of all
the possible paths, and the one

01:16:04.840 --> 01:16:05.530
thing--

01:16:05.530 --> 01:16:07.180
the one tricky
thing about this is

01:16:07.180 --> 01:16:09.510
you need to build
in a decision rule.

01:16:09.510 --> 01:16:11.320
Such that, if the system--

01:16:11.320 --> 01:16:14.330
if demand exceeds
capacity the system,

01:16:14.330 --> 01:16:16.660
you're going to expand and
move to the next stage,

01:16:16.660 --> 01:16:19.810
you're going to stage
deploy the next phase.

01:16:19.810 --> 01:16:22.780
And there's many different ways
of doing this decision rule.

01:16:22.780 --> 01:16:25.270
So the simplest one
was chosen here,

01:16:25.270 --> 01:16:27.590
and of course costs
are discounted.

01:16:27.590 --> 01:16:30.790
So let me explain to
you how this works.

01:16:30.790 --> 01:16:37.070
So we start the simulation, so
the first initial deployment.

01:16:37.070 --> 01:16:39.400
This is our initial stage one--

01:16:39.400 --> 01:16:41.200
right-- for the constellation.

01:16:41.200 --> 01:16:45.700
And then we start
operating for two years,

01:16:45.700 --> 01:16:47.380
and demand in this
period goes up.

01:16:47.380 --> 01:16:50.230
You see the ops cost in this
case goes slightly down,

01:16:50.230 --> 01:16:51.790
this is due to the discounting.

01:16:51.790 --> 01:16:53.290
This is a discounting effect.

01:16:53.290 --> 01:16:56.200
We arrive at the end of
our first three year period

01:16:56.200 --> 01:16:59.890
and then the question is here
is our capacity of the system.

01:16:59.890 --> 01:17:01.692
What would you do
in this situation?

01:17:01.692 --> 01:17:03.400
Let me ask somebody
at MIT, make sure you

01:17:03.400 --> 01:17:05.920
guys are still with me.

01:17:05.920 --> 01:17:10.580
So what would you do
in this situation?

01:17:10.580 --> 01:17:12.796
You're now at the
end of year three.

01:17:16.732 --> 01:17:18.450
Anybody?

01:17:18.450 --> 01:17:20.200
AUDIENCE: We lost you
for a second halfway

01:17:20.200 --> 01:17:23.680
through your statement,
could you repeat?

01:17:23.680 --> 01:17:27.330
PROFESSOR: Yes, so you've
done your initial three years,

01:17:27.330 --> 01:17:29.940
you've deployed your
initial constellation.

01:17:29.940 --> 01:17:32.640
And you now have the
situation shown on this chart.

01:17:32.640 --> 01:17:35.970
What's the right decision,
according to the decision rule?

01:17:45.280 --> 01:17:46.750
What's the right decision?

01:17:52.140 --> 01:17:54.900
AUDIENCE: OK, I'd
keep it the same.

01:17:54.900 --> 01:17:55.400
Because--

01:17:55.400 --> 01:17:56.400
PROFESSOR: Yes, exactly.

01:17:56.400 --> 01:17:58.750
AUDIENCE: --it has not
exceeded demand yet.

01:17:58.750 --> 01:18:00.090
But prepare to change--

01:18:00.090 --> 01:18:01.590
PROFESSOR: Exactly,
you wait, right?

01:18:01.590 --> 01:18:04.609
AUDIENCE: Because you have
to lower your capacity.

01:18:04.609 --> 01:18:06.900
PROFESSOR: You keep it the
same, you don't do anything.

01:18:06.900 --> 01:18:08.370
You just keep operating.

01:18:08.370 --> 01:18:09.520
Exactly, right.

01:18:09.520 --> 01:18:14.550
So you have another
three years, right?

01:18:14.550 --> 01:18:17.550
During these three years,
demand keeps growing.

01:18:17.550 --> 01:18:21.190
And you now, at year six,
arrive at this point here.

01:18:21.190 --> 01:18:23.040
So what's the
right decision now?

01:18:23.040 --> 01:18:25.248
AUDIENCE: Can I ask a
question about the decision

01:18:25.248 --> 01:18:28.920
to stay the same?

01:18:28.920 --> 01:18:31.920
PROFESSOR: Would
you say the same?

01:18:31.920 --> 01:18:35.684
What's happening
to the demand line?

01:18:35.684 --> 01:18:37.600
Veronica, what's happening
to the demand line?

01:18:37.600 --> 01:18:39.391
AUDIENCE: Can I ask a
quick question first,

01:18:39.391 --> 01:18:42.226
about the decision
to stay the same?

01:18:42.226 --> 01:18:42.850
PROFESSOR: Yes.

01:18:42.850 --> 01:18:46.060
AUDIENCE: I feel like by waiting
until we've exceeded demand

01:18:46.060 --> 01:18:47.890
to choose to expand
the constellation,

01:18:47.890 --> 01:18:51.310
we're introducing a lag
between demand and capability

01:18:51.310 --> 01:18:53.890
that creates an inefficiency
that may actually drive users

01:18:53.890 --> 01:18:54.890
away from the system.

01:18:54.890 --> 01:18:56.890
And I see this kind of
oscillatory effect, where

01:18:56.890 --> 01:18:59.530
you would expand, and
then people would meet,

01:18:59.530 --> 01:19:01.750
and then the system
would be insufficient

01:19:01.750 --> 01:19:03.820
and then people would move
to a different system.

01:19:03.820 --> 01:19:06.940
And you kind of have a yo-yo
around the maximum carrying

01:19:06.940 --> 01:19:07.787
capacity.

01:19:07.787 --> 01:19:09.370
And that doesn't
seem efficient to me,

01:19:09.370 --> 01:19:12.654
so I'm wondering if you
could speak to that.

01:19:12.654 --> 01:19:13.320
PROFESSOR: Yeah.

01:19:13.320 --> 01:19:15.910
AUDIENCE: So what
you're essentially

01:19:15.910 --> 01:19:20.170
looking for is what I would
[INAUDIBLE] decision rule.

01:19:20.170 --> 01:19:21.570
So you would actually--

01:19:21.570 --> 01:19:24.030
so the decision here
is to deploy, right?

01:19:24.030 --> 01:19:26.760
You've got to deploy your
second stage because you've

01:19:26.760 --> 01:19:28.980
saturated the system.

01:19:28.980 --> 01:19:33.520
What you're arguing for
is before this occurs,

01:19:33.520 --> 01:19:36.540
you know like at 80%
saturation, that's

01:19:36.540 --> 01:19:38.790
when you trigger the
next stage, right?

01:19:38.790 --> 01:19:42.810
In order to anticipate
the saturation.

01:19:42.810 --> 01:19:45.120
And so, absolutely,
you could do this.

